<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-054-204  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 054 204.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Jan 15 1990 v6 n2 p110(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Recipe for PC training: tell users why.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Logical Operations Inc. (surveys).andO;Topic:     Training of EmployeesSoftware packagesUser TrainingMicrocomputers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Recipe for PC Training:andM;Tell Users WhyandM;PC users get more out of software training when they know why they're beingtrained.andM;That's one finding of a recent study commissioned by Logical Operations Inc.,andO;a Rochester, N.Y., training firm.andM;The survey was given to 212 employees from Fortune 500 companies who hadtaken a one-day class in Lotus 1-2-3, and who, when surveyed six monthslater, believed the training had made them more productive.andM;The survey asked those users what factors had helped make the training moreproductive.andP;  Among their answers: Supervisors told them what they wereexpected to do with the software, and they themselves had some ideas for howto use the software on their jobs.andM;&quot;When a supervisor showed interest and had expectations for the user, thatperson did much better,&quot; said Harvey Feldstein, vice president of sales andmarketing at Logical Operations.andM;Among the other success factors were whether the user had some experiencewith the software before the training, and whether the user's co-workers usedthe same package and could provide an informal support network.andM;Practice helped too, said Feldstein.andP;  &quot;Those who practiced four days a weekafter training had much higher success rates than those who didn't,&quot; he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>